The inventor's presently known best mode of practicing the present invention is described in the following detailed description, which should be considered in conjunction with the accompanying drawings.


In the drawings:


FIG. 1 is a block diagram which illustrates the normal, unconnected state of the originating and receiving computers;


FIG. 2 illustrates typical entries in the initiating computer's receiving computer contact table, a database;


FIG. 3 illustrates typical entries in the receiving computer's connection request table, a database;


FIG. 4 is a flow chart identifying the processing blocks of the initiating computer and the receiving computer and the interaction between them;


FIG. 5 is a block diagram which illustrates a transient PSTN connection between the originating and receiving computers used for signaling the receiving computer;


FIG. 6 is a block diagram which illustrates an established Internet connection by the originating and receiving computers;


FIG. 7 is a block diagram which illustrates the first alternative embodiment controlling communication between three, or more, computers;


FIG. 8 is a block diagram of the novel fax call-back device;


FIG. 9 is a block diagram which illustrates the normal, unconnected state of the originating and receiving fax callback devices;


FIG. 10 is a block diagram which illustrates a transient PSTN connection between the originating and receiving fax callback devices used for signaling the receiving callback devices;


FIG. 11 is a block diagram which illustrates an established Internet connection by the originating and receiving fax callback devices; and


FIG. 12 is a flow chart identifying the processing blocks of the fax machine and fax call-back device system of FIGS. 9-11.
